00:15:15.990 --> 00:15:17.406
Is there anything
else that you've

00:15:17.406 --> 00:15:19.410
used to convince them
that actually they've

00:15:19.410 --> 00:15:23.430
got to think a little bit
differently about this?

00:15:23.430 --> 00:15:27.800
JEFF NAMNUM: Kevin and I have
two different little vignettes

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:31.720
that we're big fans
of in that situation.

00:15:31.720 --> 00:15:34.370
And Kevin's is-- and
I'll tell it wrong,

00:15:34.370 --> 00:15:35.710
and Kevin will correct it later.

00:15:35.710 --> 00:15:40.510
Find Kevin later, and he will
tell this in the clever way.

00:15:40.510 --> 00:15:43.540
The stepchild theory, right?

00:15:43.540 --> 00:15:48.080
Android users are damn
tired of being the stepchild

00:15:48.080 --> 00:15:50.540
with the hand-me-downs.

00:15:50.540 --> 00:15:55.200
Here is your Instagram
app eight months later,

00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:57.030
stripped down in functionality.

00:15:57.030 --> 00:15:57.780
And you know what?

00:15:57.780 --> 00:16:01.871
It looks just like an iOS
app and functions like one.

00:16:01.871 --> 00:16:06.310
And it doesn't feel right
to people, and they hate it.

00:16:06.310 --> 00:16:07.560
They hate it.

00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:11.000
I tend to talk more about
the ratings spiral, right?

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:15.490
Android users, they're
going to be vocal.

00:16:15.490 --> 00:16:17.840
And they're going to vote
with their thumbs, right?

00:16:17.840 --> 00:16:22.640
They're going to give you
the lowest star rating.

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:27.850
And the second you dip below
4, really, but let's say 3.5,

00:16:27.850 --> 00:16:30.520
people are thrilled
to give you 1s, right?

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:33.540
If you're above a 4,
then they're like, damn,

00:16:33.540 --> 00:16:35.500
if I give this guy
a 1, it's like me.

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:36.660
It's all me.

00:16:36.660 --> 00:16:39.310
But you're 3.5,
they're like, nope,

00:16:39.310 --> 00:16:41.970
I'm thrilled to
just pile on the 1s.

00:16:41.970 --> 00:16:43.620
And then it's just
[BUZZING SOUND].

00:16:43.620 --> 00:16:47.190
And that comes from not
feeling an experience, right?

00:16:47.190 --> 00:16:48.780
Now we tell those
little stories,

00:16:48.780 --> 00:16:55.330
but then really and truly it
is that design-- design has

00:16:55.330 --> 00:16:58.700
to be centered on
a user, and it has

00:16:58.700 --> 00:17:03.830
to be educated by the context
of that user, in whatever that--

00:17:03.830 --> 00:17:07.440
and the context shifts
in different situations.

00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:11.390
But in the situation of mobile,
a very important context

00:17:11.390 --> 00:17:15.550
is the platform that
they're used to.

00:17:15.550 --> 00:17:19.750
And you would never,
ever have a designer

00:17:19.750 --> 00:17:24.150
with no experience in
iOS design an iOS app,

00:17:24.150 --> 00:17:26.210
unless you just
had money to burn

00:17:26.210 --> 00:17:28.675
and didn't care about results.

00:17:28.675 --> 00:17:32.150
And people relate to
that very quickly.

00:17:32.150 --> 00:17:35.340
RYAN BATEMAN: I would
say a good-- yeah,

00:17:35.340 --> 00:17:38.940
building on that, a good
kind of thing we push

00:17:38.940 --> 00:17:39.737
is the [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:39.737 --> 00:17:40.820
Yeah, that's a great idea.

00:17:40.820 --> 00:17:41.320
Cool.

00:17:41.320 --> 00:17:44.010
So we take that
basis of the design.

00:17:44.010 --> 00:17:46.270
We'll do just another
design for our own sake,

00:17:46.270 --> 00:17:47.830
because we have our own opinion.

00:17:47.830 --> 00:17:49.788
And then we'll do some
very basic user testing,

00:17:49.788 --> 00:17:53.922
because we try and push
user research-based design.

00:17:53.922 --> 00:17:54.880
And oh, look, surprise.

00:17:54.880 --> 00:17:58.440
Oh, the iOS design doesn't
